            <p>July 2 1890<lb/>
                Boston Ab 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5650<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd. Dr. S. Morais<lb/>
                My very dear Doctor<lb/></p>
            <p>Your&#39;s recd. with enclosures<lb/> which I now return &#38; after carefully<lb/> reading the letters I think the very<lb/> best thing is to get the proper<lb/> estimates of what a new building<lb/> will cost with a large lot of Land<lb/> so that at any future a larger<lb/> building could be <sic>errected</sic> but could<lb/> have nothing to do unless an absolute<lb/> deed of the Land is purchased let<lb/> a responsible party give exact figures<lb/> they would <sic>errect</sic> the building &#38; Land &#38;<lb/> after the fast will do my best to <sic>cary</sic><lb/> out your wishes with kind regards to all<lb/> in which my<lb/> blessed children<lb/> join<lb/> Yours faithfully<lb/> Alfred A Marcus<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Regarding <hi rend="underline">the Old Building<lb/> <sic>Dont</sic> let them foreclose the<lb/> property I will pay all due<lb/> on it</hi><lb/></p>
            <p>Let me know just how much is<lb/> really <hi rend="underline">needed</hi><lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Return to ALFRED A. MARCUS &#38; SON&#44;<lb/>
                127 Dartmouth St.&#44; Hard by the Bridge&#44;<lb/>
                BOSTON&#44; Mass&#44; U. S. A.&#44;<lb/>
                If not delivered within 7 days.<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd Dr. S. &#91;...&#93;<lb/>
                546. N. 7&#91;...&#93;<lb/>
                Philada&#91;...&#93;<lb/></p>
            </body>
